ents","type":"User","site_admin":false}],"milestone":null,"comments":3,"created_at":"2022-02-19T10:48:36Z","updated_at":"2022-03-25T01:10:19Z","closed_at":"2022-03-25T01:10:18Z","author_association":"COLLABORATOR","active_lock_reason":null,"body":"\"good first issue\" for those with good experience in testing.\r\n\r\nA useful type of class to have for testing would be mock estimators.\r\n\r\nWhat should such a mock class do?\r\n* behave like an estimator of a specific kind, e.g., forecaster, or classifier - returns correct outputs for given inputs. Bonus if it can cover many independent tag settings, although for the start we may be happy with just a few (e.g., multiple mocks that cover specific tag combinations)\r\n* write an internal log of all calls to it, especially arguments passed and outputs requested, using private scitype defining methods like `_fit` and `_predict`\r\n\r\nThe logs can then be retrieved in tests to see what pieces of code interacting with the mock are doing.\r\n\r\nTwo use cases for this:\r\n* testing the base classes, by checking how the base class interacts with methods of the child class, like `_fit` and `_predict`\r\n* testing compositors, by checking how the composite interacts with components, a special case is #2089\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n- [ ] @ltsaprounis agreed to create a forecaster mock","closed_by":{"login":"fkiraly","id":7985502,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjc5ODU1MDI=","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/7985502?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/fkiraly","html_url":"https://github.com/fkiraly","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/fkiraly/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/fkiraly/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/fkiraly/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/fkiraly/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/fkiraly/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/fkir